SENATE BILL 901
G1 6lr3391
CF HB 1027
By: Senators Brooks, Lam, and Muse
Introduced and read first time: February 6, 2026
Assigned to: Education, Energy, and the Environment
A BILL ENTITLED
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Election Law – Telephone Voting System – Requirements
3 FOR the purpose of requiring the State Board of Elections to select, certify, and acquire a
4 telephone voting system for absentee voting by voters who have attested to having a
5 print disability that meets certain requirements; providing for the eligibility of a
6 voter to use the telephone voting system; requiring the State Board to place certain
7 voters on the telephone voting system list; requiring the State Board to send certain
8 voters on the telephone voting system list a certain communication with certain
9 information by a certain day; requiring the State Board to develop and implement a
10 certain voter education campaign; and generally relating to a telephone voting
11 system.
12 BY adding to
13 Article – Election Law
14 Section 9–102.1
15 Annotated Code of Maryland
16 (2022 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
17 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
18 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
19 Article – Election Law
20 9–102.1.
21 (A) (1) IN THIS SECTION THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
22 INDICATED.
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from exist in g l aw . *sb0901*

2 SENATE BILL 901
1 (2) “ACCESSIBLE FORMAT” MEANS BRAILLE, LARGE PRINT, AUDIO,
2 OR DIGITAL TEXT THAT IS USED BY BLIND OR VISUALLY IMPAIRED INDIVIDUALS OR
3 INDIVIDUALS WITH A PRINT DISABILITY.
4 (3) “PRINT DISABILITY” MEANS A CONDITION THAT PREVENTS OR
5 INHIBITS AN INDIVIDUAL FROM READING, HOLDING, OR PROCESSING STANDARD
6 PRINTED MATERIALS IN THE ORIGINAL FORMAT.
7 (B) (1) NOTWITHSTANDING ANY OTHER PROVISION OF LAW, THE STATE
8 BOARD, IN CONSULTATION WITH THE LOCAL BOARDS, SHALL SELECT AND CERTIFY
9 A TELEPHONE VOTING SYSTEM FOR ABSENTEE VOTING BY ELIGIBLE VOTERS WHO
10 HAVE ATTESTED TO HAVING A PRINT DISABILITY THAT MEETS THE REQUIREMENTS
11 OF THIS SECTION.
12 (2) THE TELEPHONE VOTING SYSTEM SELECTED AND CERTIFIED
13 UNDER PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS SUBSECTION SHALL BE USED IN ALL COUNTIES.
14 (3) THE STATE BOARD SHALL ACQUIRE THE TELEPHONE VOTING
15 SYSTEM SELECTED AND CERTIFIED UNDER PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS SUBSECTION.
16 (C) (1) THE STATE BOARD MAY NOT CERTIFY A TELEPHONE VOTING
17 SYSTEM UNLESS THE STATE BOARD DETERMINES THAT THE VOTING SYSTEM WILL:
18 (I) PROTECT THE SECRECY OF THE BALLOT;
19 (II) PROTECT THE SECURITY OF THE VOTING PROCESS;
20 (III) RECORD ALL VOTES ACCURATELY;
21 (IV) PROTECT ALL OTHER RIGHTS OF VOTERS AND CANDIDATES;
22 (V) BE CAPABLE OF CREATING A PAPER RECORD OF ALL VOTES
23 CAST SO THAT AN AUDIT TRAIL IS AVAILABLE IN THE EVENT OF A RECOUNT,
24 INCLUDING A MANUAL RECOUNT;
25 (VI) SECURELY AUTHENTICATE THE IDENTITY OF THE VOTER
26 BEFORE ALLOWING A BALLOT TO BE CAST, INCLUDING THROUGH THE USE OF
27 PERSONAL IDENTIFICATION NUMBERS, VOICEPRINT, OR OTHER TECHNOLOGY;
28 (VII) PROMPT A VOTER TO SELECT FROM THE OPTIONS FOR EACH
29 CONTEST OR QUESTION, ONE CONTEST OR QUESTION AT A TIME, IN THE SAME
30 ORDER AS PRINTED ON THE PRINTED BALLOT, AND CONFIRM THE VOTER’S VOTE
31 FOR EACH CONTEST OR QUESTION ON THE BALLOT;

SENATE BILL 901 3
1 (VIII) ENCRYPT THE RESULTS OF THE VOTED BALLOT ON
2 CONFIRMATION BY THE VOTER THAT THE VOTER HAS FINISHED VOTING;
3 (IX) STORE VOTED BALLOTS IN AN AIR–GAPPED, REMEMBERING,
4 NON–INTERNET CONNECTED SYSTEM;
5 (X) PRINT VOTED BALLOTS INTO A SCANNABLE PAPER BALLOT
6 OR BE TRANSCRIBED IN THE SAME MANNER AS ABSENTEE BALLOTS PROVIDED BY
7 THE INTERNET;
8 (XI) BE ACCESSIBLE THROUGH A TOLL–FREE NUMBER; AND
9 (XII) PROHIBIT A VOTER FROM CASTING MORE THAN ONE
10 BALLOT.
11 (2) THE STATE BOARD MAY NOT CERTIFY A TELEPHONE VOTING
12 SYSTEM UNLESS:
13 (I) THE TELEPHONE VOTING SYSTEM HAS BEEN:
14 1. EXAMINED BY AN INDEPENDENT TESTING
15 LABORATORY THAT IS APPROVED BY THE U.S. ELECTION ASSISTANCE
16 COMMISSION; AND
17 2. SHOWN BY THE TESTING LABORATORY TO MEET THE
18 PERFORMANCE AND TEST STANDARDS FOR VOTING SYSTEMS ESTABLISHED BY THE
19 FEDERAL ELECTION COMMISSION OR THE U.S. ELECTION ASSISTANCE
20 COMMISSION; AND
21 (II) THE PUBLIC INTEREST WILL BE SERVED BY THE
22 CERTIFICATION OF THE VOTING SYSTEM.
23 (D) A VOTE CAST THROUGH THE TELEPHONE VOTING SYSTEM SHALL BE
24 CANVASSED WITH OTHER ABSENTEE BALLOTS.
25 (E) (1) A VOTER IS ELIGIBLE TO USE THE TELEPHONE VOTING SYSTEM IF
26 THE VOTER SUBMITS A FORM TO THE STATE BOARD ATTESTING THAT THE
27 INDIVIDUAL HAS A PRINT DISABILITY.
28 (2) A VOTER WHO SUBMITS A PROPER FORM UNDER PARAGRAPH (1)
29 OF THIS SUBSECTION SHALL BE PLACED ON THE TELEPHONE VOTING SYSTEM LIST
30 BY THE STATE BOARD.

4 SENATE BILL 901
1 (F) (1) NOT LESS THAN 75 DAYS BEFORE THE DAY ON WHICH A LOCAL
2 BOARD BEGINS TO SEND ABSENTEE BALLOTS TO VOTERS, THE STATE BOARD SHALL
3 SEND A WRITTEN COMMUNICATION, USING AN ACCESSIBLE FORMAT CHOSEN BY THE
4 VOTER, TO EACH VOTER WHO IS ON THE TELEPHONE VOTING SYSTEM LIST.
5 (2) THE COMMUNICATION REQUIRED UNDER PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS
6 SUBSECTION SHALL INCLUDE:
7 (I) CONFIRMATION THAT THE VOTER IS ON THE TELEPHONE
8 VOTING SYSTEM LIST;
9 (II) THE TOLL–FREE TELEPHONE NUMBER THAT THE VOTER
10 MAY USE TO ACCESS THE TELEPHONE VOTING SYSTEM;
11 (III) THE DATES DURING WHICH THE VOTER MAY ACCESS THE
12 TELEPHONE VOTING SYSTEM;
13 (IV) CREDENTIALS TO AUTHENTICATE THE VOTER’S IDENTITY;
14 (V) INSTRUCTIONS ON HOW TO USE THE TELEPHONE VOTING
15 SYSTEM; AND
16 (VI) CONTACT INFORMATION FOR VOTER ASSISTANCE.
17 (G) THE STATE BOARD SHALL DEVELOP AND IMPLEMENT A VOTER
18 EDUCATION CAMPAIGN TO PROVIDE INFORMATION TO THE PUBLIC, AND
19 SPECIFICALLY VOTERS WITH A PRINT DISABILITY, OF THE AVAILABILITY OF THE
20 TELEPHONE VOTING SYSTEM.
21 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That, on or before December 1,
22 2028, the State Board of Elections shall report to the Senate Education, Energy, and the
23 Environment Committee and the House Government, Labor, and Elections Committee, in
24 accordance with § 2–1257 of the State Government Article, on:
25 (1) the telephone voting system selected and certified by the State Board
26 in accordance with § 9–102.1 of the Election Law Article, as enacted by Section 1 of this
27 Act;
28 (2) the status and timeline for fully implementing the telephone voting
29 system;
30 (3) the cost of acquiring, administering, and implementing the telephone
31 voting system;

SENATE BILL 901 5
1 (4) the status of the voter education campaign required under § 9–102.1(g)
2 of the Election Law Article, as enacted by Section 1 of this Act; and
3 (5) projections on the number of voters who may be eligible to use the
4 telephone voting system.
5 SECTION 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
6 January 1, 2027.

